snippet.textDisplay:
Actually, I find weird borders a bit interesting, at least pre Schengen, when they seem to raise all kinds of questions about how they're administered, especially if the countries come into conflict or at least poor relations. What happens to you if you're living in a one house exclave surrounded by a country that yours is now at war with, or dispute with? Even if you're not treated as a potential spy or sent to an internment camp, what about simple things like permitting?

Did this river-wide border allow citizens of either country to boat along it (without having to stay one side of a centerline) I'm musing, or neither without special permit (to make it easier for each side's border guards to monitor) I could imagine in distrustful times?

snippet.textDisplay: There are parts of the U.S.-Canada border which are funny too. Rue Canusa has a wicked diagonal line right through it which divides the two countries. snippet.textDisplay: 0:00 👏

There are two rivers in the US that have a border running through them, but instead of the borders being in the center of the river, they are on one of the banks so that one of the states "owns" the entire width of the river.  The Connecticut river between Vermont and New Hampshire is owned by New Hampshire from Moore Reservoir southward, and the Potomac River between Virginia/West Virginia and Maryland/Washington DC is owned by Maryland and Washington, DC.

snippet.textDisplay:
I think, if a crime were committed on the bridge by a German citizen against a German citizen, regardless of how close to either end, it should be considered to have occurred in Germany. If it were committed by a German against a Luxembourgish person, or a Luxembourgite against a German, or if it were a victimless crime like vandalism, it would have occurred on whichever side was closest. Or maybe if it were something like vandalism it would also be simpler to say it happened in the offender's country, and also it's their country's responsibility to repair the vandalism or whatever.
Luxembourgese
Luxembourgic
Luxembourgi
Luxembourgsh
Luxembourgan
Luxembourgitude
